		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31608617">Very relevant TEDx talk by Phil Hansen on &quot;The Power of Constraints&quot;: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BgoAFS3xu74" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BgoAFS3xu74</a>  (Some of the more interesting examples start at around 4 minutes in)<br />
<br />
Hansen speaks broadly about limitations being a source of creativity.  (Budget constraints are not the focus of the talk, but one example he does discuss the idea of working with a limited art budget.)<br />
<br />
To use one example from anime to illustrate this point, I'll turn back to my post in last week's Sayonara Zetsubou Sensei discussion:<br />
<br />
<div class="quotetext">One of the things that keeps me coming back to Sayonara Zetsubou Sensei is the animation. Remember that Shaft produced this in 2007. Right now, Shaft is a studio that is flooded with cash, but their big windfall didn't happen until 2008 (with the blu-ray release of the wildly successful Bakemonogatari). Before that, Shaft operated on a poverty-tier budget. And through the circumstances of this anime's production, I learned that Akiyuki Shinbo had this weird talent for taking budget animation and making it look creative rather than shoddy.<br />
<br />
For example, see this hastily-made GIF: <a href="http://cdn.makeagif.com/media/6-08-2014/T58fWS.gif" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://cdn.makeagif.com/media/6-08-2014/T58fWS.gif</a><br />
<br />
The cloth is textured (with little &quot;x&quot; shapes) but the texture remains static while the cloth moves. Obviously, it's cheaper to animate the cloth in this manner, and it sticks out. It looks clearly &quot;off.&quot; But rather than looking like a cheap cost-saving measure, the visual is so unashamed that it comes across as avant garde. And this example is just one of many.<br />
<br />
The big thing I'd like to emphasize is how incredibly pervasive these cost-saving animation techniques are. They're present in practically every scene of every episode of SZS, whether it comes down to framing shots in a way that reduces the amount of space that needs to be animated or recycling frames (there are lots of places where you'll have a stretch of 10-15 seconds with fewer than a dozen unique frames). The anime is absolutely riddled with little quirks like these--things that save money, but instead of looking cheap they come across as creative and original.<br />
<br />
When I think of anime that really pioneer creative animation, I think of Sayonara Zetsubou Sensei. I strongly believe that limitations and constraints can breed creativity, and SZS is an excellent example of that in effect.<!--quote--></div></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
