		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31768537">I don't think budget is that constraining.<br />
<br />
Gundam SEED has a p cool budget. It's one of the most expensive shows in history and yet, it looks... average. The director wanted to do some super robots shit like have cool stock fight scenes and that didn't go well with real robots. And the screenwriter suffered from cancer. No one wanted to let her go so we had recaps. It's p cool.<br />
<br />
I think scheduling is more constraining than budget. With Shaft, it's not the budget (they are after all Aniplex's bitch) but the scheduling. Why else do their shows in BDs look so different? Currently, Shaft is doing like three shows and they're not very good at being consistent in one show. I expect Mekakucity Actors to look like a normal anime instead of... whatever it is right now.<br />
<br />
I also like to mention that HapiCha suffer not from budget from terrible staff. They get outsourced to Toei Philippines and that guy who does SSO, resulting in some derpy faces. Outsourcing is generally a bigger problem too. Love Lab's shittiest episode comes from a random Korean animation group while the rest of them looks good or really really good.<br />
<br />
I also think a limited budget can be beneficial. What Kuiper said is p cool. But this could happen: Saki S1 is animated mostly by Gonzo. Until Gonzo died. Then, a really good animation studio (the name is floating from my head) takes over and makes everything good. The swimming pool episode is animated by one person. It's also a good case that sometimes outsourcing is good.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I don't think lower budgets are bad. Constraints are powerful if you know how to use it. That said, I don't think budgets are as big of a constraint as scheduling.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">I work in <!--link--><a href="http://vntls.tindabox.net/staff/kastel" rel="nofollow">VNs</a>. Sometimes, they have h-scenes and I go "waai~". I also like to not write at <!--link--><a href="http://oppaiisjustice.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow">Oppai is Justice</a>, a blog with great urls.</div></td>
