		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31871145">Two shows immediately come to mind when talking about shows with a low budget, but used it effectively. Those two are Jojo's Bizarre Adventure and Samurai Flamenco. I suppose Samurai Flamenco wasn't too special with what it did; it seemed to sacrifice art quality for higher frame rate which isn't the worst way to go I suppose. But for what it wanted to do which was bring an exaggerated crazy world, I think it did a fantastic job. Jojo's Bizarre Adventure on the other hand was much more creative; it used weird colour schemes and camera angles which showcased bizarre poses to convey it's over the top nature. Neither of these shows was really hindered by a low budget, though a bigger budget would always have been nicer.<br />
<br />
On the other side of the spectrum, we have shows with obviously large budgets but bad handling of it. A1 Pictures is a studio famous for this; at least for people who are good enough at spotting bad animation as it seems A1 is great at making the average viewer think it's shows have good animation. Sword Art Online is the best example I can think of. It obviously has a large budget with gorgeous backgrounds, consistent artwork, beautiful soundtrack and big names in the production team. But when it came down to it, the animation was pretty bad. It used a lot of flash and movement lines to mimic animation where in fact it was just vibrating still images. Several fights didn't even have the killing blow be an actual strike, but rather just a coloured line to imply a sword swing. This was okay in the 70s when animation was weak, but to do that today on a big budget is just incredibly lazy. The reason people believe SAO to have good animation I believe is because of the consistent character designs and backgrounds.<br />
<br />
So yeah, I don't think budgets really matter with anime. I think Jojo and Samurai Flamenco are two of the most entertaining shows ever made and they've got low budgets yet have made the most of what they had. SAO has a huge budget and I think it's a terrible show with terrible allocation of said budget. In this sense, I've got to give more credit to the people working behind the shows. The people who made Jojo and Samurai Flamenco were definitely passionate about making their show. The guys behind SAO seemed much more cynical and more about producing an easy cash grab since I'm sure hiring high quality VAs, composers, singers etc are much easier to do than actually animating an anime.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
